  <text>
      <body>
         <p>Dear Sir, I received your letter of —— acknowledging the receipt of my work on the mysteries including Freemasonry — stating that you had not fully perused it and therefore had not made up your option in regard to the probability of the sale of a republication of it in Englan.d
            the bearer of this resides in this city, and will soon return. i should like to hear farther from you on the subject by him.</p>
         <p>we understand that you are lecturing on the holy scriptures, showing them to be mainly allegorical— i have <persName>Sir <forename>William</forename> <surname>Drummond</surname>'s <idno></idno> </persName> work on the subjects; and find it very plaussible [sic] in respect to many parts of this holy book. this fact being proved renders the bible null and void as to its inspiration.</p>
         <p>i am now concerned in the editing of a liberal work, entitled the Beacon – of which i send you the numbers as far printed.—</p>
            <p>the bearer is waiting —</p>
            <p>yours sincerely</p>
            <p>john fellows</p>
